            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " for definitions and conventions used for real input."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The correct interpretation of the hermitian input depends on the shape of\nthe original data, as given by "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "s"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". This is because each input shape could\ncorrespond to either an odd or even length signal. By default, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "irfftn"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "\nassumes an even output length which puts the last entry at the Nyquist\nfrequency; aliasing with its symmetric counterpart. When performing the\nfinal complex to real transform, the last value is thus treated as purely\nreal. To avoid losing information, the correct shape of the real input\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "strong",
              "text": "must"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " be given."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
